# NestJS Conventions

## Server App Structure

```
apps/<name>-server/
  package.json                   â†’ extends shared deps pattern
  tsconfig.json                  â†’ extends tsconfig.nest.json
  nest-cli.json                  â†’ SWC builder + typeCheck
  eslint.config.mjs              â†’ imports { nestServer } from @primer-guidy/eslint-config
  src/
    main.ts                      â†’ bootstrap: NestFactory + ValidationPipe + listen on PORT env
    app.module.ts                â†’ imports HealthModule, LlmModule.register([...]), feature modules
    modules/
      <feature>/
        <feature>.module.ts
        <feature>.controller.ts
        <feature>.service.ts
        <feature>.repository.ts  â†’ (if data access needed)
        dto/                     â†’ (app-specific DTOs only)
        guards/                  â†’ (app-specific guards only)
```

## Shared Modules â€” `@primer-guidy/nest-shared`

Before creating any module, check if `@primer-guidy/nest-shared` already provides it:

| Module | Usage |
|--------|-------|
| `HealthModule` | Import directly â€” provides `GET /health` |
| `LlmModule.register([...])` | Configure LLM providers with token + env var mappings |
| `ApiKeyGuard` | Apply via `@UseGuards(ApiKeyGuard)` for server-to-server auth |
| `PromptContextDto` | Use as `@Body()` parameter for prompt + context endpoints |
| `GenerationResponseDto` | Return type for LLM generation responses |

```typescript
// app.module.ts â€” typical server setup
import { HealthModule, LlmModule } from '@primer-guidy/nest-shared'

@Module({
  imports: [
    HealthModule,
    LlmModule.register([
      { token: 'ILlmProvider', modelEnv: 'OLLAMA_MODEL', defaultModel: 'llama3.1:8b' },
    ]),
    FeatureModule,
  ],
})
export class AppModule {}
```

## Shared Configs

ALL NestJS servers MUST use the shared configs:

| Config | Path | What it provides |
|--------|------|-----------------|
| `tsconfig.nest.json` | `../../tsconfig.nest.json` | CommonJS, node resolution, decorators, strict mode |
| `nestServer` ESLint | `@primer-guidy/eslint-config` | `no-extraneous-class` off for modules, `consistent-type-imports` off for DI files |
| `nest-cli.json` | Per server (identical) | SWC builder with typeCheck |

Server `tsconfig.json` MUST extend `tsconfig.nest.json` and add only `outDir` + `rootDir`:

```json
{
  "extends": "../../tsconfig.nest.json",
  "compilerOptions": { "outDir": "dist", "rootDir": "src" },
  "include": ["src/**/*"],
  "exclude": ["node_modules", "dist", "**/*.test.ts"]
}
```

## Single Responsibility per Service

Each service handles ONE domain concern. Never mix responsibilities.

```typescript
// BAD â€” mixed concerns
@Injectable()
class UserService {
  createUser() { /* ... */ }
  sendWelcomeEmail() { /* ... */ }
  generateReport() { /* ... */ }
}

// GOOD â€” separated
@Injectable()
class UserService { createUser() { /* ... */ } }
@Injectable()
class NotificationService { sendWelcomeEmail() { /* ... */ } }
@Injectable()
class ReportService { generateReport() { /* ... */ } }
```

## Layer Responsibilities

| Layer | Responsibility |
|-------|---------------|
| Controller | HTTP handling, validation, response shaping |
| Service | Business logic, orchestration |
| Repository | Data access, query building |

- Controllers NEVER access repositories directly
- Services NEVER handle HTTP concerns (request/response objects)
- Repositories NEVER contain business logic

## DTOs & Validation

- Use `class-validator` + `class-transformer` for all DTOs
- Separate `CreateDto`, `UpdateDto`, `ResponseDto` per entity
- NEVER expose internal entities in API responses
- Check `@primer-guidy/nest-shared` for shared DTOs before creating new ones

## LLM Integration

- Inject LLM providers via `@Inject(TOKEN)` using tokens defined in `app.module.ts`
- NEVER import from `ollama` or `groq-sdk` directly â€” use `@primer-guidy/llm-services`
- System prompts are constants in the service file that uses them
- Use low temperature (0-0.3) for classification/validation, higher (0.7) for generation

## Docker

- ALL servers use the shared `docker/Dockerfile.server` (parameterized via `APP_NAME` and `APP_PORT` build args)
- NEVER create per-server Dockerfiles
- Server-to-server communication uses Docker network hostnames in local, Cloud Run URLs in production
